post_text:
Saydel Folks,

Here's a fun little article I wanted to share with all of you from the December 31, 1961 Sunday issue of the Des Moines Register that highlights the then upcoming bond referendum for the original Cornell Elementary School Building. Enjoy :)

Highlights:
The original bond issue to build the first phase of Cornell as well as a 4 classroom addition to Norwoodville Elementary was $400,000 and 30,000 SF = $13.69/SF. Comparatively, you would spend between $240-$330/SF for new construction today or $7.2M-$9.9M, a 2500% increase in cost between 1961 and today - talk about inflation!

The passage of the bond issue allowed the district to close 4 substandard country style schoolhouses, two of which did not have modern plumbing.

From the 1954 formation of the Saydel consolidated school district to when the article was written 8 years later, the school district attempted 4 separate bond referendums and voters never turned down a bond issue, they all passed!

Parents and Guardians;

The following survey is designed to provide you input regarding Saydel CSD's Return to Learn Planning process. Our intent is to design the following models to better serve our stakeholders: Onsite, Hybrid, and Virtual. Please know the IDOE requires schools to have plans in place to address the full spectrum of scenarios as it relates to COVID-19. Once we have the plans built, we will communicate with our public accordingly. Please take a few minutes to provide us invaluable feedback for this important work by following the link below for the Return to Learn Parent Survey.

https://forms.gle/6c9yfpkF3WVufxxw5

We thank you for your ongoing support and partnership during this unprecedented crisis; it is much appreciated and illustrates great unity.

Yours in service,

Todd A. Martin, Superintendent

post_text:
COVID-19 Communication to Families and Staff;

This evening Governor Reynolds recommended Iowa schools close for four weeks to help mitigate the spread of COVID-19. The recommendation was made in consultation with the Iowa Department of Public Health (IDPH) and based on CDC guidelines.

Saydel Community School District will follow the advice and cancel all programs, Eagles Nest, activities, and classes effectively immediately.

We will be sending out more information following the Governor's press conference as we learn more about expectations for Iowa school closures.

We understand there is a great amount of uncertainty and concern among our families, staff, and community. We will work to keep everyone well informed and continue to ensure the safety of our students, staff, and community.

Yours in Service,
Todd A. Martin

post_text: Board elections were held Nov. 5th, 2019 in which we had four candidates running for four open seats in the Saydel CSD. Gary Christensen II (new), Jennifer Van Houten (incumbent), Doug Kayser (incumbent), and Chad Vitiritto (incumbent) were all elected and will join Directors Beth Shelton, Julie Jennings, and Roland Kouski Jr. on our new board. On Nov. 18th, 2019 we retired our old board and invited our newest member, Director Christensen, to join the team. We also elected a new board president and vice president to preside over the Saydel Board of Directors. It is our honor to announce that Julie Jennings was sworn in as our newest board president, and Jennifer Van Houten was elected as our vice president. Please congratulate our board members on the elections and let them know you appreciate their hard work in doing great things for our district.

Saydel Community School District is participating in the Summer Food Service Program. Meals will be provided to all children without charge and are the same for all children regardless of race, color, national origin, sex, age or disability, and there will be no discrimination in the course of the meal service. No identification or registration is required. All sites will be closed on July 4 in observance of the Fourth of July holiday.

Meals will be provided, at a first come, first serve basis, at the site and times as follows:

LOCATIONS

Cornell Elementary
June 3-Aug. 9
Breakfast served 8:00am–9:00 a.m.
Lunch served 11:30 a.m.–12:30 p.m.
